04738nam a22005535i 9780226331447DE-B159720220629043637.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220629t20212016ilu    fo  d z      eng d  a2015015469  a9780226331447  a(DE-B1597)568135  a(OCoLC)1233040921  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ailucUS-IL00aQH362b.L33 2016 4aQH362b.L33 2016 7aEDU0000002bisacsh04a576.80762231 aLaats, Adam, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aTeaching Evolution in a Creation Nation /cHarvey Siegel, Adam Laats. 1aChicago : bUniversity of Chicago Press, c[2021] 4c©2016  a1 online resource (144 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aHistory and Philosophy of Education Series00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction: The Evolution of an Educational Controversy -- t1 Higher Education and a New Culture of Science -- t2 Evolution Education in a Jazz Age -- t3 The Dog That Didn’t Bark -- t4 A New Minority -- t5 Evolution, Creation, Science, Religion, and Public Education -- t6 Beyond “Creation Science”: The Scientific Status of Intelligent Design -- t7 Science Education: Aims and Constraints; Belief versus Understanding -- t8 A Question of Culture? -- tConclusion: Evolution as Education -- tNotes -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aNo fight over what gets taught in American classrooms is more heated than the battle over humanity’s origins. For more than a century we have argued about evolutionary theory and creationism (and its successor theory, intelligent design), yet we seem no closer to a resolution than we were in Darwin’s day. In this thoughtful examination of how we teach origins, historian Adam Laats and philosopher Harvey Siegel offer crucial new ways to think not just about the evolution debate but how science and religion can make peace in the classroom. Laats and Siegel agree with most scientists: creationism is flawed, as science. But, they argue, students who believe it nevertheless need to be accommodated in public school science classes. Scientific or not, creationism maintains an important role in American history and culture as a point of religious dissent, a sustained form of protest that has weathered a century of broad—and often dramatic—social changes. At the same time, evolutionary theory has become a critical building block of modern knowledge. The key to accommodating both viewpoints, they show, is to disentangle belief from knowledge. A student does not need to believe in evolution in order to understand its tenets and evidence, and in this way can be fully literate in modern scientific thought and still maintain contrary religious or cultural views. Altogether, Laats and Siegel offer the kind of level-headed analysis that is crucial to finding a way out of our culture-war deadlock.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 0aCreationismxStudy and teaching. 0aEducationzUnited StatesxReligious aspects. 0aEvolution (Biology)xStudy and teaching. 7aEDUCATION / General.2bisacsh  aeducation, social aspects, creationism, philosophy, biology, nature, history, united states, educational policy, evolution, evolutionary science, american classrooms, origins, humanity, theory, intelligent design, resolution, charles darwin, thoughtful examination, debate, controversy, religion, religious thought, public school, dissent, culture, protest, modern knowledge, cultural views, culture-war deadlock, teaching, students, pareants, politics, political.1 aSiegel, Harvey, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press Complete eBook-Package 2016z978311071098440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226331447